dens, city farms (Northey Street City Farm, Brisbane). Shared at gardening open days. Some online nurseries.", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "Australian Native Yams", "slug": "australian-native-yams", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "Pencil Yam / Long Yam (Dioscorea transversa)", "slug": "pencil-yam-long-yam-dioscorea-transversa", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Indigenous to eastern and northern Australia. Staple food of Australian Aboriginal peoples for thousands of years", "traits": "Slender, long cylindrical tubers (hence ''pencil yam''). Heart-shaped shiny leaves with 5-7 prominent veins. Rounded seed pods dry to papery straw brown texture, persist for months", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate yields, tubers 5-15cm long", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Indigenous nurseries, bushfood suppliers. University of Queensland research programs. Limited availability - conservation focus.", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "Native Warrain Yam (Dioscorea hastifolia)", "slug": "native-warrain-yam-dioscorea-hastifolia", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Endemic to Western Australia (not naturally occurring in Brisbane area, but included for reference)", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "Lesser Yam (Standard)", "slug": "lesser-yam-standard", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Southeast Asia (likely Burma or Indo-China), cultivated for thousands of years. One of first yam species domesticated", "traits": "Smaller than greater yam. Vines seldom exceed 3m. Compact growth habit allows closer spacing. Multiple small tubers per plant", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "15-25 t/ha, lower than greater yam but still productive", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Asian grocers, ethnic markets in Brisbane. Less common than greater yam but available seasonally.", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "Chinese Yam (Standard)", "slug": "chinese-yam-standard", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "East Asia (China, Korea, Japan). Cultivated for over 2000 years. Introduced to USA in 1800s, Europe in 1800s", "traits": "Spindle-shaped or cylindrical tubers up to 1m long, weighing up to 4.5kg. More frost-tolerant than other yams. Produces abundant aerial bulbils 4cm long. Cinnamon-scented flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High-yielding, comparable to potato fields per acre", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Asian markets (Korean, Japanese, Chinese grocers). Fresh tubers sometimes available. Specialty nurseries stock plants.", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "White Yam (Standard)", "slug": "white-yam-standard", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to West Africa (Nigeria, Ghana, Benin, Ivory Coast). Independently domesticated in Africa. Introduced to Asia and Americas", "traits": "Cylindrical tubers, smooth brown skin, white firm flesh. Tubers typically 2-10kg, can reach 25kg. Vines 10-12m long, may have small spines at leaf axils", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "30-40 t/ha in optimal conditions, single large tuber per plant", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "African grocers, international markets in Brisbane. Increasingly available as Brisbane''s African community grows.", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "Yellow Yam (Standard)", "slug": "yellow-yam-standard", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to West Africa (Guinea, Senegal to Nigeria). Now cultivated in Caribbean and tropical Americas", "traits": "Similar appearance to white yam but yellow flesh from carotenoids. Tuber skin less grooved, firmer. Longer vegetative period, sho